Creating neutral landscapes for ecological models with NLMPY

An instruction to use NLMPY from within R

Marco Sciaini, spatialrecology.org

Department of Ecosystem Modelling, University of Gttingen

2017-01-20

Basics

There are a plethora of standalone software packages out there to create neutral landscape models, unfortunalety is the only R package (ecomodtools) to achieve this no longer available. Hence, the python library NLMPY by Etherington, Holland, and OSullivan (2015Etherington, Thomas R, E Penelope Holland, and David OSullivan. 2015. NLMpy: A Python Software Package for the Creation of Neutral Landscape Models Within a General Numerical Framework. Methods in Ecology and Evolution 6 (2). Wiley Online Library: 16468.) is right now the most versatile tool to create artificial landscapes in a coding workflow and it can be embedded into larger modelling frameworks based on software that is capable of executing a Python script, such as R.

NLMPY produces two-dimensonal arrays by performing different neutral landscape model algorithms (Fig. 1). Furthermore, NLMPY allows the user to blend and classify every raster. With this, novel combinations of algorithms can be achieved. The package is capable of doing a lot more, but here we will limit its use to create only landscapes. If you want to dig deeper, have a look on the linked paper and their Youtube introductions: installing, using.

Fig. 1: Bestiary of neutral landscape models (Etherington et al. 2014). The figure shows all realisations of the implemented algorithms and some of the possibilities of how to blend them. For a full description go here.

Setup Python

The use of NLMPY requires the following things installed:

  • Python 2.7.3
  • NumPy 1.8.0
  • SciPy 0.13.2
  • Matplotlib 1.3.1

The setup for this should be no problem for people on UNIX systems.

However, on Windows numpy and scipy are (in my experience) quite hard to install. To make it easy, I suggest the use of a precompiled python distribution, which comes already shipped with these two packages and pip (python package to easily install other python packages). I chose Anaconda and on that relies the following tutorial. If you choose another distribution, take care with the system paths I will use to setup PythonInR.

Connect R to python

To run python code from within R we will use the R package PythonInR. Again, on UNIX system this is very handy - load the package and you can skip the following the step.

On Windows, the python.exe must be explicitly linked1 After executing this code, you should read something like: Initialize Python Version 2.7.12 |Anaconda 4.2.0 (64-bit)| (default, Jun 29 2016, 11:07:13) [MSC v.1500 64 bit (AMD64)] in your R console.:

# setup python connection ----
python <- 'C:/Users/Marco/Anaconda2/python.exe' 
pyConnect(pythonExePath=python)

Python code

I wrote the following python code to create an imagenary scenario that we want to run from within R:

import os
os.chdir("path/to/your/folder") # you need to adjust this to your setting
import nlmpy 
import numpy as np

# set up generation of landscapes
np.random.seed(1)   
nRow = 210          
nCol = 100          

# create midpoint-displacement array
nlmmpd = nlmpy.mpd (nRow, nCol, h = 0.75)

# create distance gradient array 
nlmdist = np.zeros((nRow, nCol))
nlmdist[208:210, 40:60] = 1
nlmdist[9:10, 1] = 1
nlmdist = nlmpy.distanceGradient(nlmdist)

# blend mdp and distance gradient arrays
nlmmpddist = nlmpy.blendArray(nlmmpd, [nlmdist])

# classify the blended array in three classes
nlmmpddistclass = nlmpy.classifyArray(nlmmpddist, [1,1,1])

# export as ASCII grid
nlmpy.exportASCIIGrid("nlmmpddistclass.asc", nlmmpddistclass)

Put everything together

If we now want to perform the generation of our desired landscape in R, we assign the python code as character vector to an object called init_landscape and execute it:

# load packages ----
library(PythonInR)

# setup python connection ----
python <- 'path/to/your/folder'
pyConnect(pythonExePath=python)

# create object containing the python code to create neutral landscapes ----
init_landscape <- '
import os
os.chdir("path/to/your/folder") 
import nlmpy 
import numpy as np

# set up generation of landscapes
np.random.seed(1)   
nRow = 210         
nCol = 100         

# create midpoint-displacement array
nlmmpd = nlmpy.mpd (nRow, nCol, h = 0.75)

# create distance gradient array 
nlmdist = np.zeros((nRow, nCol))
nlmdist[208:210, 40:60] = 1
nlmdist[9:10, 1] = 1
nlmdist = nlmpy.distanceGradient(nlmdist)

# blend mdp and distance gradient arrays
nlmmpddist = nlmpy.blendArray(nlmmpd, [nlmdist])

# classify the blended array in three classes
nlmmpddistclass = nlmpy.classifyArray(nlmmpddist, [1,1,1])

# export as ASCII grid
nlmpy.exportASCIIGrid("nlmmpddistclass.asc", nlmmpddistclass)
'

# execute python code to create neutral landscapes ----
PythonInR::pyExec(code = init_landscape)

The code will generate a file called nlmmpddistclass.asc in the working directory of python, which we can reimport in R (for example with the the raster package).

Neutral landscape visualization

To check the result of our python code, we import it as raster and plot it using the rasterVis package. rasterVis allows to use the ggplot syntax to plot raster objects.

# load packages ----
library(ggplot2)
library(rasterVis)
library(viridis)
library(raster)

# import raster from nlmpy ----
mpd.raster <- raster('path/to/your/folder/nlmmpddistclass.asc')

# plot and check raster from nlmpy ----
gplot(mpd.raster) + geom_tile(aes(fill = value)) +
                        coord_equal() +
                        scale_fill_viridis("") +
                        theme_void()
